Create a global selection store keyed by issue number, add visible checkboxes to both card surfaces, and surface a selection count in the kanban toolbar.

### v0.6.2-shippable scope

The issue acceptance bullets list 5 features. Cut to MVP:
- Multi-select via checkboxes (Phase 1)
- Select all / deselect all (Phase 1)
- Selection count display (Phase 1)
- Bulk close + bulk add label via toolbar (Phase 2)
- Tests for the store (Phase 3)

Deferred to a follow-up issue (file at the end):
- Shift+click range selection (UX complexity, deserves its own scope)
- Bulk YOLO (terminal/state coordination)
- Bulk assign-to-release (release form integration)
- Bulk remove label (label-picker UX is the same; the feature is symmetric and adds value but doubles the toolbar code; defer to follow-up)

This matches the v0.6.0/v0.6.1 pattern of shipping focused MVPs and filing follow-ups.

### New file: `apps/desktop/src/stores/selectionStore.ts`

Mirror existing store patterns (kanbanStore for persist setup, issuesStore for the action shape). Selection is **per-project** but **NOT persisted** — selection is transient UI state; reloading should clear it.

```ts
import { create } from 'zustand';
import { useProjectsStore } from './projectsStore';

interface SelectionState {
  /** Per-project selected issue numbers. */
  selectedByProject: Record<string, Set<number>>;
}

interface SelectionActions {
  toggle: (issueNumber: number) => void;
  selectMany: (issueNumbers: number[]) => void; // sets these as selection (replace)
  addMany: (issueNumbers: number[]) => void;    // unions into existing
  clear: () => void;
  isSelected: (issueNumber: number) => boolean; // convenience
  count: () => number;
  selected: () => number[]; // sorted ascending
}

const getProjectId = (): string => useProjectsStore.getState().activeProjectId ?? 'default';

export const useSelectionStore = create<SelectionState & SelectionActions>((set, get) => ({
  selectedByProject: {},

  toggle: (n) => set((state) => {
    const pid = getProjectId();
    const existing = state.selectedByProject[pid] ?? new Set<number>();
    const next = new Set(existing);
    if (next.has(n)) next.delete(n); else next.add(n);
    return { selectedByProject: { ...state.selectedByProject, [pid]: next } };
  }),

  selectMany: (numbers) => set((state) => {
    const pid = getProjectId();
    return { selectedByProject: { ...state.selectedByProject, [pid]: new Set(numbers) } };
  }),

  addMany: (numbers) => set((state) => {
    const pid = getProjectId();
    const existing = state.selectedByProject[pid] ?? new Set<number>();
    const next = new Set(existing);
    numbers.forEach((n) => next.add(n));
    return { selectedByProject: { ...state.selectedByProject, [pid]: next } };
  }),

  clear: () => set((state) => {
    const pid = getProjectId();
    if (!state.selectedByProject[pid]) return state;
    return { selectedByProject: { ...state.selectedByProject, [pid]: new Set() } };
  }),

  isSelected: (n) => {
    const pid = getProjectId();
    return get().selectedByProject[pid]?.has(n) ?? false;
  },

  count: () => {
    const pid = getProjectId();
    return get().selectedByProject[pid]?.size ?? 0;
  },

  selected: () => {
    const pid = getProjectId();
    const set_ = get().selectedByProject[pid];
    return set_ ? [...set_].sort((a, b) => a - b) : [];
  },
}));
```

Note: `Set` cannot be partialized cleanly via the persist middleware — that's another reason to keep selection NOT persisted.

